description:
In crates/unbrk-core/src/error.rs, ConsoleTail::new accepts impl Into<Vec<u8>>, converts to Vec, then calls from_buffer which creates a new Vec from the tail slice:

  pub fn new(bytes: impl Into<Vec<u8>>) -> Self {
      let bytes = bytes.into();
      Self::from_buffer(bytes.as_slice())
  }

When called with a Vec<u8> (as in uboot.rs run_command and cli wait_for_uboot_prompt), the original Vec is allocated, converted, then immediately discarded after from_buffer copies the tail into a new Vec. The signature should be impl AsRef<[u8]> instead:

  pub fn new(bytes: impl AsRef<[u8]>) -> Self {
      Self::from_buffer(bytes.as_ref())
  }

Impact is minimal since ConsoleTail::new is only called on error paths, but this is a needless allocation that violates own-borrow-over-clone.

In crates/unbrk-core/src/flash.rs, the verify_total_size function returns Ok(()) when parse_total_size fails to find the Total Size summary in the loadx output:

  let Ok(total_size) = parse_total_size(output) else {
      return Ok(());
  };

This design is intentional because the Total Size line is optional (some U-Boot builds may not emit it). However, the silent success means there is no observable indication that verification was skipped. If U-Boot output is truncated or garbled, the missing verification would go unnoticed. The function should emit a diagnostic event or at minimum return an enum that distinguishes verified/skipped so the caller can log it. Currently the caller has no way to know whether the Total Size check passed or was simply absent.

Both RecoveryRunner::emit (recovery.rs) and FlashRunner::emit (flash.rs) use this pattern:

  let event = Event::now(sequence, payload.clone())
      .unwrap_or_else(|_| Event::new(sequence, 0, payload));

The .clone() on EventPayload (which contains heap-allocated Strings) exists solely to handle the edge case where SystemTime::now() returns Err (system clock before Unix epoch). This is astronomically unlikely on any real system. The fix is to compute the timestamp separately first:

  let timestamp = timestamp_now_unix_ms().unwrap_or(0);
  let event = Event::new(sequence, timestamp, payload);

This requires either making timestamp_now_unix_ms pub(crate) or extracting a shared helper. Both emit methods should be updated. Impact is minor since emit is not a hot path, but the clone allocates for each of the ~15 events emitted per recovery.
